WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.240
Are you ready to dive into your next Python project, but feeling a bit overwhelmed by

00:00:05.240 --> 00:00:10.040
where to begin? Or perhaps you're worried about your new code clashing with existing

00:00:10.040 --> 00:00:14.120
projects on your machine? In this video, we'll guide you through the

00:00:14.120 --> 00:00:20.320
essential steps to set up a robust and isolated Python development environment. We'll leverage

00:00:20.320 --> 00:00:26.840
Positron, Posit's powerful new IDE to get you started on the right coding path, ensuring

00:00:26.840 --> 00:00:30.840
your projects are organized, efficient, and headache free.

00:00:30.840 --> 00:00:36.040
To install Positron, you'll want to visit the website here at the top of the screen.

00:00:36.040 --> 00:00:40.500
You'll also need to ensure Python is installed on your machine.

00:00:40.500 --> 00:00:48.240
After opening Positron, we'll want to first create a new Python project.

00:00:48.240 --> 00:00:53.880
After selecting Next, we'll then change the name of our project to PydyTuesday. This will

00:00:53.880 --> 00:00:59.639
create a new folder called PydyTuesday in the parent directory located in the text box

00:00:59.639 --> 00:01:03.720
below. Finally, it's always a good idea to initialize

00:01:03.720 --> 00:01:08.440
your project as a Git repository so that we can leverage version control.

00:01:08.440 --> 00:01:14.519
Finally, it's time to tell Positron how to set up our Python environment. We'll create

00:01:14.519 --> 00:01:22.919
a brand new, isolated, virtual environment using venv. This is crucial because it keeps

00:01:22.919 --> 00:01:28.519
your project's dependencies entirely separate from other Python projects on your machine,

00:01:28.519 --> 00:01:34.199
preventing any conflicts or crosstalk. After that, we'll simply select our preferred

00:01:34.199 --> 00:01:40.120
Python interpreter and click Create. We are given the option to open the new project

00:01:40.120 --> 00:01:47.160
in the current Positron window or open a new window. Let's select New Window.

00:01:47.160 --> 00:01:52.760
And there it is! You successfully created a new Python project in Positron. Notice that

00:01:52.760 --> 00:01:57.959
there is a blank Python file, making it incredibly easy to jump right in and start coding.

